
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `autoconf` yek barname ast baraye sakhtan script-haye configure. In script-ha komak mikonand barname-haye shoma ro rooye system-haye mokhtalef compile konid, bedoon ehtiaj be dastkari-haye ziad. Yani code-haye shoma ro ba system-haye dige *sazgar* mikone.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `autoconf` --> ⚙️ Sakhtan script `configure` az `configure.ac` (ya `configure.in`).
    🔹 `autoconf --help` --> ℹ️ Namayesh rahnama (help) baraye dastoor `autoconf`.
    🔹 `autoconf --version` --> 🔢 Namayesh version `autoconf`.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ autoconf

    🔹 Script `configure` ra az file `configure.ac` misazad.

    $ autoconf my_config.ac

    🔹 Agar esme file shoma `configure.ac` nabashad, mitavanid an ra moshakhas konid.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ autoconf

    🔹 Agar file `configure.ac` dar pooshe-ye shoma voojood dashte bashad, script `configure` sakhte mishavad. Ba'd az aan, shoma mitavanid az dastoor `./configure` estefade konid ta barname-ye shoma ro baraye compile amade konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `autoconf` command is a tool for generating configure scripts. These scripts help you compile your programs on different systems without significant manual adjustments.  It makes your code *compatible* with different systems.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `autoconf` --> ⚙️ Generate the `configure` script from `configure.ac` (or `configure.in`).
    🔹 `autoconf --help` --> ℹ️ Display help information for the `autoconf` command.
    🔹 `autoconf --version` --> 🔢 Display the version of `autoconf`.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ autoconf

    🔹 Generates the `configure` script from the `configure.ac` file.

    $ autoconf my_config.ac

    🔹 If your file isn't named `configure.ac`, you can specify it.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ autoconf

    🔹 If a `configure.ac` file exists in your directory, a `configure` script will be created. After that, you can use the `./configure` command to prepare your program for compilation.
